    "( 22) is to obtain an isomorphism of Hilbert spaces, see Theorem B.1.",
    "Actions of Tube algebrasLet C be a region such that Σ C has compact boundary.",
    "To each connected boundary component S ∈ Bd(Σ C) we associate a collar region C S, defined to be the smallest subregion of C such that S ∈ Bd(Σ C S).",
    "Note that if C contains a face f and C ′ is obtained from C by removing f, then Σ C ′ has a connected boundary component at f which we denote by S f. We denote the corresponding collar region byC f:= C S f. More generally, if N ⊂ S ∈ Bd(Σ C) then we let C N be the smallest subregion of C so that N ⊂ ∂Σ C N. The region C N does not depend on S in the sense that if N ⊂ S ′ in Bd(Σ C ′) for some other region C ′, then C N is also the smallest subregion of C ′ such that N ⊂ ∂Σ C N.For each S ∈ Bd(Σ C) we define a representation t S of Tube S on H C S as follows.",
    "First, for any a ∈ Tube S, the operator t S (a) acts as zero on the orthogonal complement of the string-net subspace H C S. That is, any t S (a) enforces string-net constraints on the collar region C S.On the string-net subspace, the action is given byt S (a) ϕ:= σ -1 C S a ▷ S σ C S (ϕ)(23)for any ϕ ∈ H C S. It follows from Lemma B.1 that each t S is a *-representation of Tube S. Let us also define a *-representation of Tube op Ŝ on H C S by t op S (a):= t S (a op) (24) for any a ∈ Tube Ŝ. Unpacking definitions and making use of Convention 4.2, the action of t S ([y]) on H C S is represented graphically by t S         = δ x S,y Ŝ d y S d x S 1/4."
